| {{flagicon|UK}} [[Johnny Herbert]]\n| [[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 1:16.250\n| +2.139\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 18\n| 20\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Marc Gen\u00e9]]\n| [[Minardi]]-[[Fondmetal]]\n| 1:16.380\n| +2.269\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 19\n| 15\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Nick Heidfeld]]\n| [[Prost Grand Prix|Prost]]-[[Peugeot]]\n| 1:17.112\n| +3.001\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 20*\n| 16\n| {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Pedro Diniz]]\n| [[Sauber]]-[[Sauber Petronas Engineering|Petronas]]\n| 1:17.178\n|  +3.067{{ref|1|1}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 21\n| 21\n| {{flagicon|Argentina}} [[Gast\u00f3n Mazzacane]]\n| [[Minardi]]-[[Fondmetal]]\n| 1:17.512\n| +3.401\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 22*\n| 17\n| {{flagicon|Finland}} [[Mika Salo]]\n| [[Sauber]]-[[Sauber Petronas Engineering|Petronas]]\n| 1:18.703\n|  +4.592{{ref|1|1}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" |[[107% time]]: 1:19.299\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" |Source:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.statsf1.com/en/2000/bresil/qualification.aspx|title=Brazil 2000 \u2013 Qualifications|publisher=Stats F1|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181114224142/http://www.statsf1.com/en/2000/bresil/qualification.aspx|archive-date=14 November 2018|url-status=live|access-date=14 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=ESPNResults/>\n|}\n'''Notes:'''\n\n* {{note|1|1}}{{snd}}Sauber withdrew [[Pedro Diniz]] and [[Mika Salo]] on the grounds of safety due to separate [[Spoiler (car)|rear wing]] failures on their cars.<ref name=SauberBumps/>\n\n==Warm-up==\n\nA 30-minute warm-up session was held on Sunday morning in hot and overcast weather.<ref name=FIAWarmUp>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fia.com/presse/f1news-a/Bresil3-2000.htm|title=Grand Prix of Brazil: Warm-Up|date=26 March 2000|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20001025192224/http://www.fia.com/presse/f1news-a/Bresil3-2000.htm|archive-date=25 October 2000|url-status=dead|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> All drivers fine-tuned their race set-ups and set laps in their spare cars.<ref name=FIAWarmUp/> H\u00e4kkinen set the session's fastest lap at 1 minute and 16.343 seconds, ahead of Michael Schumacher, Coulthard, Barrichello, Verstappen, Ralf Schumacher, Gen\u00e9, Fisichella and Zonta in positions two to ten.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2183.htm|title=Sunday Warm-Up \u2013 Brazilian GP|date=26 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422092357/http://atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2183.htm|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> Ten minutes in,<ref name=F1NetWarmUp>{{Cite web|url=http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=3549|title=Hakkinen on top before race|date=26 March 2000|publisher=F1Racing.net|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050318214815/http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=3549|archive-date=18 March 2005|url-status=dead|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> Wurz [[Stall (engine)|stalled]] his car at the exit of the pit lane, and the session was stopped as he took the spare [[Benetton B200]] setup for his teammate Fisichella.<ref name=FIAWarmUp/> Alesi's engine failed and he switched to the spare [[Prost AP03]], which had a rear wing failure on the bumpy start/finish straight, and caused a second stoppage.<ref name=FIAWarmUp/><ref name=F1NetWarmUp/>\n\nAfter the warm-up session, and before the race, Prost examined Alesi's rear wing and found that its failure was due to older bodywork parts fitted to his car and readied its spare chassis if required. The team stated they were unconcerned over the safety of their drivers and confirmed their participation in the event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8514|title=Prost to enter Brazilian GP|date=26 March 2000|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512103212/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8514|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Race==\nThe race began at 14:00 local time.<ref name=\"GF1Race\">{{cite web|title=Report: Michael Wins Again!|url=http://dbs.galeforcef1.com/event_report.asp?n=2000032622h10&s=2000&e=02|publisher=Gale Force F1|date=26 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070503010450/http://dbs.galeforcef1.com/event_report.asp?n=2000032622h10&s=2000&e=02|archivedate=3 May 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> The weather at the start was hot and dry with the ambient temperature {{Convert|22|C|F|abbr=}}, the track temperature {{Convert|35|C|F|abbr=}}, and the humidity at 76%.<ref name=\"GF1Race\" /><ref name=\"F1COMBrazilRace\">{{cite web|title=2000: Round 2 \u2013 Brazil: Interlagos|url=http://www.formula1.com/races/racenews00/brazil/race.html|publisher=Formula1.com|date=26 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010210201517/http://www.formula1.com/races/racenews00/brazil/race.html|archivedate=10 February 2001|url-status=dead}}</ref> Approximately 72,000 spectators attended the race.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A60969592/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=014ffc19|title=Motor racing: Schumacher's Title Warning|last=Gordon|first=Ian|date=27 March 2000|work=[[The News Letter]]|access-date=12 May 2019|page=23|via=Infotrac Newsstand|url-access=subscription}}</ref> On the [[Parade lap|formation lap]], Wurz stalled his engine,<ref name=DF1RaceQuotes>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailyf1.com/en/results/2000/02/quotes-sun.shtml|title=The Brazilian Grand Prix 2000: Team and driver comments \u2013 Sunday|date=26 March 2000|publisher=Daily F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010702070823/http://www.dailyf1.com/en/results/2000/02/quotes-sun.shtml|archive-date=2 July 2001|url-status=dead|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> and his stationary car delayed Alesi and Herbert; both drivers took up their starting positions.<ref name=AF1Report/> Wurz began from the pit lane.<ref name=FIARace>{{cite web|title=Grand Prix of Brazil: Race Facts and Incidents|url=http://www.fia.com/presse/f1news-a/Bresil4-2000.htm|publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|date=26 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001025204953/http://www.fia.com/presse/f1news-a/Bresil4-2000.htm|archivedate=25 October 2000|url-status=dead}}</ref> H\u00e4kkinen made a brisk start from the grid to lead the field going into the Senna S chicane.<ref name=MCOMRace>{{cite web|last=M. Baines|first=Stephen|title=Brazilian GP Report|url=https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/brazilian-gp-report-2002-04-15/40163/|publisher=motorsport.com|date=26 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510070618/https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/brazilian-gp-report-2002-04-15/40163/|archive-date=10 May 2019}}</ref> Coulthard, in second, had [[wheelspin]] and was passed by Michael Schumacher, who unsuccessfully challenged H\u00e4kkinen for the lead. He retained third as Barrichello made a slow getaway.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" /> Behind them, Irvine overtook Fisichella for fifth. Verstappen moved from 14th to 11th by the conclusion of the first lap; Button dropped from 9th to 13th over the same distance.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> Trulli passed Ralf Schumacher and Villeneuve to progress into tenth on the left of the circuit.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" />\n\n[[File:Giancarlo Fisichella 2012 WEC Fuji.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Giancarlo Fisichella]] ''(pictured in 2012)'' earned his first podium finish of the season in second.]]\n\nAs the first two drivers reached the start/finish line,<ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /> Michael Schumacher, who was close behind H\u00e4kkinen throughout lap one,<ref name=\"F1RacingNetRace\">{{cite web|title=Schu-master wins in Brazil|url=http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=3562|publisher=F1Racing.net|date=26 March 2000|accessdate=10 May 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050318212739/http://www.f1racing.net/en/news.php?newsID=3562|archivedate=18 March 2005|url-status=dead}}</ref> steered off the racing line to pass the latter for the lead heading into the Senna S chicane.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" /> Barrichello [[Drafting (aerodynamics)|slipstreamed]] Coulthard on the start/finish straight and overtook him for third.<ref name=\"F1RacingNetRace\" /> He then made a driver error and Coulthard retook third. Barrichello retook the position by the end of lap two as Coulthard lost the use of the first three gears and was slower in the slow-speed corners.<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /> Upfront, Michael Schumacher extended his lead over H\u00e4kkinen to four seconds by lap four and to 15 seconds by lap 15 with a series of [[fastest lap]]s. In the meantime, Trulli passed Zonta to move into eighth, Button overtook Alesi for 13th and Heidfeld lost 16th to de la Rosa. Verstappen progressed from 11th to seventh by passing Villeneuve, Zonta, Frentzen and Fisichella as Alesi overtook Ralf Schumacher, Villeneuve, Zonta and Frentzen to advance to ninth.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> Three drivers retired from the race during this period: Wurz and Heidfeld had separate engine failures on lap seven and nine and Alesi stopped with an electrical failure at the Bico de Pato hairpin on lap 11.<ref name=\"F1COMBrazilRace\" /><ref name=\"AF1Report\" />\n\nAt the end of lap 14, Barrichello drew close to H\u00e4kkinen after the latter made a driver error. He slipstreamed H\u00e4kkinen and turned left to pass him for second under braking the Senna S chicane to start the 15th lap.<ref name=\"F1COMBrazilRace\" /><ref name=\"AF1Report\" /><ref name=\"F1RacingNetRace\" /> De la Rosa passed Herbert for 14th on that lap and Trulli overtook Irvine for fifth on lap 16.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> That lap, Villeneuve retired with a race-long gearbox problem. The Ferrari and McLaren teams employed different pit stop strategies \u2013 the Ferrari team planned for two stops whereas the McLaren squad scheduled one stop.<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /> Michael Schumacher led by 17.6 seconds over the rest of the field when he commenced the first round of pit stops for fuel and tyres four laps later.<ref name=\"GF1Race\" /> He rejoined the track in third and Barrichello led the next two laps until his stop.<ref name=\"AutosportLapByLap\">{{cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8515|title=Brazilian Grand Prix: Lap by lap|date=26 March 2000|work=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512103201/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8515|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live|accessdate=10 May 2019}}</ref> On lap 21, Irvine lost control of the rear of his car entering the Bico de Pato hairpin and crashed against a tyre barrier. Six laps later, Barrichello entered the pit lane with a [[hydraulic motor]] problem that spread from the [[steering wheel]] to the throttle linkage.<ref name=\"F1COMBrazilRace\" /><ref name=DF1RaceQuotes/> As Barrichello exited the car to retire a small fire was extinguished by his mechanics.<ref name=\"MCOMRace\" />\n\n[[File:Michael Schumacher 01 (sk).jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Michael Schumacher]] ''(pictured in 2007)'' took his second win of the season and 37th of his career.]]\n\nTrulli made the first of two stops from fourth at the end of the 28th lap and he emerged in seventh.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> At the front of the field, H\u00e4kkinen pulled away to lead Michael Schumacher by 12 seconds until he slowed with a loss of oil engine pressure on the 30th lap.<ref name=DF1RaceQuotes/><ref name=\"AutosportLapByLap\" /> He slowed and retired in his garage. Michael Schumacher retook the lead, with the yet-to-stop Coulthard second, Verstappen third and Fisichella fourth.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> Coulthard lapped to within a tenth of a second of Michael Schumacher as the latter slowed slightly due to an imbalance in all four of his tyres as Ralf Schumacher challenged Fisichella for fourth.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" /><ref name=\"MCOMRace\" /><ref name=\"F1RacingNetRace\" /> On lap 32, Gen\u00e9 retired from eleventh with an engine failure.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" /> Verstappen and his teammate de la Rosa made their first pit stops on laps 35 and 37. Four laps later, Frentzen was the first driver on a one-stop strategy to enter the pit lane.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> Coulthard made his only stop on lap 43 and remained in second position. Michael Schumacher led by 48 seconds when he made his second pit stop on the 51st lap and retained the lead.<ref name=\"F1RacingNetRace\" /> On the same lap, Fisichella made his only stop and kept third place.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" />\n\nOn lap 51, Herbert retired in the pit lane with a gearbox failure.<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /> De la Rosa lost concentration and went into a gravel trap four laps later. He rejoined without a loss of position.<ref name=\"F1COMBrazilRace\" /><ref name=\"F1RacingNetRace\" /> Button battled Verstappen and overtook him for seventh on the 56th lap as Trulli made a pit stop from fourth and rejoined the track in fifth.<ref name=\"FIARace\" /> From the 59th lap, Coulthard began to gain on Michael Schumacher, who slowed due to an [[oil pressure]] problem.<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /><ref name=\"FIARace\" /> He could not draw close enough to pass, and Schumacher took his second victory of the season, his third in Brazil and the 37th of his career in a time of 1 hour, 31 minutes and 35.271 seconds at an average speed of {{Convert|200.404|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/03/27/sports/plus-auto-racing-brazilian-grand-prix-schumacher-wins.html|title=Plus: Auto Racing \u2013 Brazilian Grand Prix; Schumacher Wins|date=27 March 2000|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=12 May 2019|agency=[[Associated Press]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512111105/https://www.nytimes.com/2000/03/27/sports/plus-auto-racing-brazilian-grand-prix-schumacher-wins.html|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=CollingsReport>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2186.htm|title=Timothy Collings' Brazilian GP Race Report|last=Collings|first=Timothy|date=26 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422092838/http://atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2186.htm|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> Coulthard followed 4.302 seconds later and Fisichella took third. Frentzen finished fourth, Trulli fifth and Ralf Schumacher sixth. Button, Verstappen, de la Rosa, Zonta and Mazzacane were the final finishers.<ref name=\"GPCOMBrazil00\" /> The attrition rate was high; only 11 of the 20 starters finishing the race.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A60827984/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=9e4e0bb1|title=Triumphant Schumacher travels light; Motor Racing|last=Eason|first=Kevin|date=27 March 2000|work=[[The Times]]|access-date=12 May 2019|page=40|via=Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n===Post-race===\nThe top three drivers appeared on the podium to collect their trophies and spoke to the media in a later press conference.<ref name=\"regulations\" /> Michael Schumacher stated that pit stop strategy helped him to win the race, \"In the past, as you may remember, we could not overtake the McLaren entries, regardless of their strategy. Now we are looking a lot more competitive \u2013 which is where we wanted to be \u2013 and the season could hardly have started better than it has.\"<ref name=PressConf>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2191.htm|title=Post-Race Press Conference \u2013 Brazilian GP|date=25 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422093049/http://atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2191.htm|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> Coulthard said his second-place finish provided him the start to of his championship campaign after his gearbox problems, \"It must have been entertaining for those who had places to watch at the first corner. Given the circumstances, I am very happy with my six points.\"<ref name=PressConf/> Fisichella revealed that his car yearned between understeer and oversteer for the first 15 laps until its grip and balance improved. Nonetheless, he said he was pleased to finish third, \"This is a great result and will help us to be even more competitive in the future. I am confident about the next race, when we will have some new aerodynamic parts.\"<ref name=PressConf/>\n\n[[File:David Coulthard 2007.jpg|thumb|upright|[[David Coulthard]] ''(pictured in 2007)'' was disqualified from second place due to an illegal front wing endplate on his car.]]\n\nAll of the top six finishers, except for Fisichella, were found to excessive wear on the wooden planks underneath their cars. Ferrari, McLaren, Benetton, Jordan and BMW filed a successful appeal on the basis the bumpy racing surface caused the illegal wear and were reinstated after a further inspection caused a {{frac|3|1|2}} hour delay.<ref name=\"AF1Report\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8531|title=Schumacher cleared as race winner|date=27 March 2000|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512152054/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/8531|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> During the inspection, the front wing endplates on Coulthard's car were found to be {{Convert|43|mm|cm|abbr=on}} above the ground and not {{Convert|50|mm|cm|abbr=on}} as stated in the regulations''.''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A75778273/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=6c8d1e8c|title=Motor Racing: McLaren 'were leant on': Team allege threats made to impound car if they did not toe line over disqualification|last=Henry|first=Alan|author-link=Alan Henry|date=28 March 2000|work=The Guardian|access-date=12 May 2019|page=9|via=General OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2193.htm|title=Coulthard's car bumps him from 2nd spot|date=27 March 2000|work=Cape Argus|access-date=12 May 2019|agency=Reuters|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303230427/http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2193.htm|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Jo Bauer]], the FIA technical delegate, deemed this to have provided Coulthard with a competitive aerodynamic advantage and the stewards disqualified the driver six hours after the race. The technical director of McLaren [[Adrian Newey]] rejected an offer from the stewards to transport Coulthard's car to Paris for a fair hearing and agreed to a set of four measurements in S\u00e3o Paulo. McLaren then filed an appeal and stated the car's undertray and chassis was damaged and shifted by vibrations from the bumps on the racing surface.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A60842541/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=08dcf78c|title=Coulthard left on wing and prayer; Motor racing|last=Eason|first=Kevin|date=28 March 2000|work=The Times|access-date=12 May 2019|page=37|via=Academic OneFile|url-access=subscription}}</ref> On 4 April, the appeal was heard by a five-man panel at a meeting of the FIA International Court of Appeal in Paris. They rejected McLaren's appeal during the 90-minute hearing and declared the result of the race final.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A103703782/GPS?u=wikipedia&sid=GPS&xid=4dd64b01|title=Coulthard loses appeal|last=Gowar|first=Rex|date=5 April 2000|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|access-date=12 May 2019|page=066|via=Infotrac Newsstand|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nThis promoted every driver behind Coulthard one position; Button was reclassified sixth and became the [[List of Formula One driver records#Youngest drivers to score points|youngest driver to score a Formula One World Championship point]] at the age of 20 years, 2 months and 7 days old, breaking [[Ricardo Rodr\u00edguez (racing driver)|Ricardo Rodr\u00edguez]]'s record from the [[1962 Belgian Grand Prix]].{{#tag:ref|The record for the youngest driver to score a Formula One World Championship point is currently held by [[Max Verstappen]], who was 17 years and 166 days old when he finished seventh at the [[2015 Malaysian Grand Prix]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Max Verstappen makes F1 history as youngest in points|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/sports/motor/formula1/2015/03/29/max-verstappen-makes-f1-history-as-youngest-in-points/70625740/|work=[[USA Today]]|agency=Associated Press|date=29 March 2015|accessdate=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>|group=\"n\"}}<ref>{{Cite journal|date=May 2000|title=Button Makes History|url=https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/archive/article/may-2000/5/button-makes-history|journal=[[Motor Sport (magazine)|Motor Sport]]|volume=LXXVI|pages=5|access-date=12 May 2019|number=5|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512152047/https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/archive/article/may-2000/5/button-makes-history|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/22058/9429909/f1-records-dont-approve|title=F1 records showing their age|last=Esler|first=William|date=21 August 2014|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826050137/https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/22058/9429909/f1-records-dont-approve|archive-date=26 August 2014|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> On 6 April, the organisers of the Brazilian Grand Prix were summoned to a meeting of the FIA General Assembly. They were fined $100,000 for the track's safety issues and for the three times qualifying was stopped due to advertising hoardings falling towards it. The governing body ruled it as \"exceptional circumstances\" and allowed the track to remain as part of the series.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/motorsport/2000/0407/148843-formula1/|title=Formula 1: FIA fine Brazilian GP organisers|date=7 April 2000|access-date=12 May 2019|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512152051/https://www.rte.ie/sport/motorsport/2000/0407/148843-formula1/|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The president of the FIA [[Max Mosley]] said an increased fine or cancelling the race was not imposed because its organisers had submitted evidence to prevent either action from occurring, \"Bearing in mind that we allowed the Brazilian promoters to place the signs there \u2013 and they probably didn't know what potential there was for the failures which occurred \u2013 it seemed only fair to impose the comparatively modest penalty.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crash.net/f1/news/35623/1/interlagos-bumps-a-part-of-f1-says-max|title=Interlagos bumps a part of F1, says Max|date=9 April 2000|publisher=Crash|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512152050/https://www.crash.net/f1/news/35623/1/interlagos-bumps-a-part-of-f1-says-max|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nH\u00e4kkinen spoke of his disappointment over retiring from the lead of the race, \"Nothing can describe how I feel, We have been quick all weekend, right the way through, so I am not happy to be leaving Brazil without any points. We have some work to do before the start of the European season.\"<ref name=CollingsReport/> Button was quoted in the press as stating his preference to score points on the track and not be awarded them in a court of appeal, \"I heard the news about David as I was making my way to the airport to fly back from Brazil \u2013 and I can't say it gave me any great feeling of joy. You want to earn any success through your driving skills, not someone else's misfortune.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/9043|title=Button prefers to make point in races|date=29 March 2000|website=Autosport|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512152050/http://classic.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/9043|archive-date=12 May 2019|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> [[Eddie Jordan]], the owner of the Jordan team, said that both his cars finishing the event demonstrated they could last a full race distance after retiring from the Australian Grand Prix with mechanical issues. Frentzen stated it was as if the team's season had commenced in Brazil and the team still required maintenance to improve their performance, \"But we are a very strong team with a good atmosphere, I get along well with Jarno and everything is fine so far.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2188.htm|title=Jordan Back in the Points in Brazil|last=Milliken|first=Mary|date=25 March 2000|website=Atlas F1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422035436/http://atlasf1.com/news/2000/mar/2188.htm|archive-date=22 April 2016|url-status=live|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe gap in the Drivers' Championship after the race stood at 12 points in favour of Michael Schumacher with Fisichella moving from fifth to second as a result of his second-place finish. Barrichello dropped to third with six points and Ralf Schumacher fell to fourth. Frentzen rounded out the top five drivers.<ref name=\"points\" /> In the Constructors' Championship, Ferrari moved further ahead with 26 points and the Benetton team progressed from fourth to second. Jordan's first points of the season put them third while Williams and BAR were fourth and fifth with fifteen races left in the season.<ref name=\"points\" />\n\n===Race classification===\nDrivers who scored [[List of Formula One World Championship points scoring systems|championship points]] are denoted in '''bold''' and by a {{double dagger}}.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |{{Abbr|Pos|Position}}\n! scope=\"col\" |{{Abbr|No.|Car number}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Driver\n! scope=\"col\" | Constructor\n! scope=\"col\" |{{Abbr|Laps|Laps completed}}\n! scope=\"col\"