ar]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 51\n| Gearbox\n| 17\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 20\n|{{flagicon|Spain}} [[Marc Gen\u00e9]]\n|[[Minardi]]-[[Fondmetal]]\n| 31\n| Engine\n| 18\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 1\n|{{flagicon|Finland}} [[Mika H\u00e4kkinen]]\n|[[McLaren]]-[[Mercedes-Benz HighPerformanceEngines|Mercedes]]\n| 30\n| Oil pressure\n| 1\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 4\n|{{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Rubens Barrichello]]\n|[[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n| 27\n| Hydraulics\n| 4\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 7\n|{{flagicon|UK}} [[Eddie Irvine]]\n|[[Jaguar Racing|Jaguar]]-[[Cosworth]]\n| 20\n| Spun off\n| 6\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 22\n|{{flagicon|Canada}} [[Jacques Villeneuve]]\n|[[British American Racing|BAR]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| 16\n| Gearbox\n| 10\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 14\n|{{flagicon|France}} [[Jean Alesi]]\n|[[Prost Grand Prix|Prost]]-[[Peugeot]]\n| 11\n| Electrical\n| 15\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 15\n|{{flagicon|Germany}} [[Nick Heidfeld]]\n|[[Prost Grand Prix|Prost]]-[[Peugeot]]\n| 9\n| Engine\n| 19\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ret\n| 12\n|{{flagicon|Austria}} [[Alexander Wurz]]\n|[[Benetton Formula|Benetton]]-[[Playlife]]\n| 6\n| Engine\n| 13\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | DSQ\n| 2\n|{{flagicon|UK}} [[David Coulthard]]\n|[[McLaren]]-[[Mercedes-Benz HighPerformanceEngines|Mercedes]]\n| 71\n| Illegal front wing endplates (+4.302)\n| 2\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | DNS\n| 16\n|{{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Pedro Diniz]]\n|[[Sauber]]-[[Sauber Petronas Engineering|Petronas]]\n| 0\n| Safety concerns\n| 0\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | DNS\n| 17\n|{{flagicon|Finland}} [[Mika Salo]]\n|[[Sauber]]-[[Sauber Petronas Engineering|Petronas]]\n| 0\n| Safety concerns\n| 0\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n! colspan=\"8\" |{{center|Source:<ref name=ESPNResults>{{cite web|url=http://en.espn.co.uk/f1/motorsport/race/2036.html?|title=2000 Brazilian Grand Prix results|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=13 March 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113140123/http://en.espn.co.uk/f1/motorsport/race/2036.html|archivedate=13 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"formula1.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.formula1.com/results/season/2000/52/ |title=2000 Brazilian Grand Prix |publisher=Formula One |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141010081255/http://www.formula1.com/results/season/2000/52/ |archivedate=10 October 2014 |accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref>}}\n|}\n\n==Championship standings after the race==\nNote, only the top five positions are included for both sets of standings.\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Drivers' Championship standings\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Pos|Position}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Driver\n! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n| 1\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Michael Schumacher]]\n| align=\"right\"| 20\n|-\n| 2\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Giancarlo Fisichella]]\n| align=\"right\"| 8\n|-\n| 3\n| {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Rubens Barrichello]]\n| align=\"right\"| 6\n|-\n| 4\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Ralf Schumacher]]\n| align=\"right\"| 6\n|-\n| 5\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Heinz-Harald Frentzen]]\n| align=\"right\"| 4\n|-\n!colspan=4|Source:<ref name=points/><ref name=\"champ\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.statsf1.com/en/2000/bresil/championnat.aspx|title=Brazil 2000 \u2013 Championship|publisher=Stats F1|access-date=13 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717211930/http://www.statsf1.com/en/2000/bresil/championnat.aspx|archive-date=17 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n;Constructors' Championship standings\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | {{Abbr|Pos|Position}}\n! scope=\"col\" | Constructor\n! scope=\"col\" | Points\n|-\n| 1\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n| align=\"right\"| 26\n|-\n| 2\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Benetton Formula|Benetton]]-[[Playlife]] <!--Benetton raced under an Italian racing licence from 1997 onwards, so must be recorded as Italian here. Thanks.--->\n| align=\"right\"| 8\n|-\n| 3\n| {{flagicon|IRE}} [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]-[[Mugen Motorsports|Mugen-Honda]]\n| align=\"right\"| 7\n|-\n| 4\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[BMW in Formula One|BMW]]\n| align=\"right\"| 7\n|-\n| 5\n| {{flagicon|UK}} [[British American Racing|BAR]]-[[Honda in Formula One|Honda]]\n| align=\"right\"| 4\n|-\n!colspan=4|Source:<ref name=points/><ref name=\"champ\"/>\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Notes and references==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=n}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{F1 race report\n| Name_of_race            = [[Brazilian Grand Prix]] \n| Year_of_race            = 2000\n| Previous_race_in_season = [[2000 Australian Grand Prix]]\n| Next_race_in_season     = [[2000 San Marino Grand Prix]]\n| Previous_year's_race    = [[1999 Brazilian Grand Prix]]\n| Next_year's_race        = [[2001 Brazilian Grand Prix]]\n}}\n{{F1GP 00-09}}\n{{Portal bar|Brazil|Sports|Formula One}}\n\n{{coord|23|42|13|S|46|41|59|W|source:kolossus-nowiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:2000 Formula One races|Brazilian Grand Prix]]\n[[Category:Brazilian Grand Prix]]\n[[Category:2000 in Brazilian motorsport|Grand Prix]]\n[[Category:March 2000 sports events in South America|Brazilian Grand Prix]]\n", "name_user": "Usernameunique", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRace:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2000_Brazilian_Grand_Prix"}
{"title_page": "Purbiyas (soldiers)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2020}}\n'''Purbiya''' (or '''Purabia''') was a common term used in medieval India for [[Rajput]]-led mercenaries and soldiers from the eastern [[Gangetic Plain]] - areas corresponding to present-day western [[Bihar]] and eastern [[Uttar Pradesh]].<ref name=\"Naravane1999\"/> ''Purbiya Rajputs'' translates as Eastern Rajputs.<ref name=\"ErnstPati2007\">{{cite book|author1=Waltraud Ernst|author2=Biswamoy Pati|title=India's Princely States: People, Princes and Colonialism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9eKbW3ukh9oC&pg=PA57|date=18 October 2007|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=978-1-134-11988-2|page=57}}</ref> In contrast, the Rajputs living in [[Rajasthan]] were historically referred to as \"Western Rajputs\".<ref name=\"Naravane1999\">{{cite book|author=M. S. Naravane|title=The Rajputs of Rajputana: A Glimpse of Medieval Rajasthan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lF0FvjG3GWEC&pg=PA23|year=1999|publisher=APH Publishing|isbn=978-81-7648-118-2|page=23}}</ref>\n\n==Recruitment==\nThe core region for Purbiya recruitment was the [[Bhojpuri region|Bhojpur]] region of modern-day Western [[Bihar]] and Eastern [[Uttar Pradesh]].<ref name=Kolff2013>{{cite journal | jstor=j.ctt6wp6pg.11 | title=Peasants fighting for a living in early modern North India | journal=Fighting for a Living | author= Dirk H.A. Kolff | publisher= Amsterdam University Press | year=2013 | pages= 243\u2013266}}</ref> The [[Ujjainiya]] clan of Rajputs were the main territorial lords of this region and they played the role of specialised recruiting agents and commanders of these Purbiya soldiers who were usually young peasant men native to Bhojpur.<ref name=Kolff2013 /> The soldiers gained a great reputation among the lords and kings of Northern and Western India and the Ujjainiyas used this to raise their status among other Rajput clans.<ref name=Kolff2013 />\n\nMany future Purbiya mercenaries would carry out a pilgrimage to [[Buxar]] in modern-day Bihar where they would immerse themselves in a ''tiger tank''. During this process, the young peasant would see themselves as being reborn as a \"fearless warrior\".<ref name=Kolff2013 />\n\n==History==\n[[File:Camel Rider,.jpg|thumb|A Purbiya camel rider in [[Bihar]], [[India]] in 1825.]]\n\nThe [[Mughal Empire|Mughals]] were among the first groups to enter into the military labour market and start recruiting Purbiyas. Mughal sources detail a diwan of Bihar [[subah]] attempting to collect soldiers in [[Buxar]] to serve the emperor.<ref name=\"Kolff2002\">{{cite book|author=Dirk H. A. Kolff|title=Naukar, Rajput, and Sepoy: The Ethnohistory of the Military Labour Market of Hindustan, 1450-1850|url=https://books.google.com/?id=SrdiVPsFRYIC&pg=PA169&dq=Kolff+Mughal+province#v=onepage&q=Kolff%20Mughal%20province&f=false|date=8 August 2002|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=978-0-521-52305-9|page=59}}</ref>\n\nThe rulers of [[Malwa]] were also keen recruiters due to Purbiyas' expertise with firearms. This expertise may have been gained due to the easy availability of [[saltpetre]] in their native areas.<ref>{{cite book|first1=Waltraud |last1=Ernst |first2=Biswamoy |last2=Pati |title=India's Princely States: People, Princes and Colonialism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9eKbW3ukh9oC&pg=PA57|year=2007|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-11988-2|page=57}}</ref> Most Purbiyas were mercenaries and were paid for their services but some were actual kings of smaller principalities.<ref name=\"Naravane1999\"/><ref>Journal of Indian history, Volume 66, Dept. of History, University of Kerala, 1988</ref>{{Pn|date=October 2016}} This recruitment drive from Malwa saw the large influx of Purbiya soldiers into the region. Many of the local chieftains in Malwa depended heavily on Purbiya soldiers such as [[Silhadi]] who eventually became known as a Purbiya himself.<ref name=\"Kolff2002\" />\nThe presence of Purbiya mercenaries in [[Gujarat]] are referenced in 16th and 17th century [[Persian language|Persian]] chronicles including many Purbiya gunners serving in the army of Bahadur Shah of the [[Gujarat Sultanate]] in 1535.<ref name=Khan1999>{{cite journal | title=Re-examining the origin and group identity of the so-called \"Purbias\", 1500-1800 | author= Iqtidar Alam Khan | journal=Proceedings of the Indian History Congress |volume = 60| year=1999 | pages= 363\u2013371|jstor = 44144102}}</ref>\n\nPurbiyas had a long tradition of being recruited as mercenaries for various rulers such as the [[British Raj|British]]<ref name=\"Hiltebeitel2009\">{{cite book|author=Alf Hiltebeitel|title=Rethinking India's Oral and Classical Epics: Draupadi among Rajputs, Muslims, and Dalits|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MMFdosx0PokC&pg=PA308|date=15 February 2009|publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]]|isbn=978-0-226-34055-5|page=308|author-link=Alf Hiltebeitel}}</ref><ref name=\"Karsten2013\">{{cite book|first=Peter|last=Karsten|title=Recruiting, Drafting, and Enlisting: Two Sides of the Raising of Military Forces|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Fh_fAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA103|date=31 October 2013|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=978-1-135-66150-2|page=103}}</ref> and the [[Marathas]].<ref name=\"ErnstPati2007\" /> Purbiyas made up the majority of the [[Bengal Army]].<ref name=\"Karsten2013\" />Prior to 1857, the British [[East India Company]] preferred to recruit Purbiya soldiers, who they designated as \"The fighting tribes of the Hindoos and the Musselmen\", or simply \"Easterners\".<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=627fBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA335 |title=Chinese and Indian Warfare \u2013 From the Classical Age to 1870 |first1=Kaushik |last1=Roy |first2=Peter |last2=Lorge |page=335|isbn=9781317587101 |date=2014-12-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Philip|last=Mason|pages=229 & 573|title=A Matter of Honour|isbn=978-0-333-41837-6|year=1986}}</ref> The [[Bengal Army]] of the East India Company preferred to recruit its sepoys from the [[Brahmin]]s and Rajputs of Awadh and Bihar, in part because they had an average height of 5'9\", an important consideration in an army that valued impressive appearance amongst its soldiers.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vRE3n1VwDTIC&pg=PA214 |title=Hinduism and the Ethics of Warfare in South Asia: From Antiquity to the Present |first=Kaushik |last=Roy |year=2012 |page=214|isbn=9781107017368 }}</ref>\n\n===1857 mutiny===\n[[File:Bengal Troops on the Line of March (6125141926).jpg|thumb|400px|Bengal troops in the 19th century (1840s), the majority of troops in the Bengal Army were Purbiyas]]\nThe Purbiya units of the Bengal Army played a major role in the [[Indian Rebellion of 1857]] against the British. [[Mangal Pandey]], a notable figure during the start of the mutiny, was a Purbiya serving in the 34th [[Bengal Native Infantry]]. Following the suppression of the uprising, British authorities decided not to recruit troops from the eastern plains, and the new Bengal Army was to be recruited primarily from the [[Sikh]] and [[Islam in India|Muslim]] communities of the [[Punjab]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=q5JECgAAQBAJ&pg=PA6 |title=Military Manpower, Armies and Warfare in South Asia |first=Kaushik |last=Roy |page=6|isbn=9781317321286 |date=2015-10-06 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Philip|last=Mason|page=305|title=A Matter of Honour|isbn=978-0-333-41837-6|year=1986}}</ref> Purbiya recruitment from the western regions of the [[United Provinces of Agra and Oudh|United Provinces]] and the [[Delhi]] region continued but on a much smaller scale (two out of sixty-four regiments by 1893).<ref>{{cite book|first=Saul|last=David|page=404|title=The Indian Mutiny|isbn=978-0-141-00554-6|date=2003-09-04}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mercenaries in India]]\n*[[Camel cavalry]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* M K A Siddiqui (ed.), ''Marginal Muslim Communities in India'', Institute of Objective Studies, New Delhi (2004)\n* [[Dasharatha Sharma]] ''Rajasthan through the Ages'' a comprehensive and authentic history of Rajasthan, prepared under the orders of the Government of Rajasthan. First published 1966 by Rajasthan Archives.\n\n[[Category:Rajputs|*]]\n[[Category:History of Bihar]]\n[[Category:Mercenary units and formations of the Early Modern era]]\n[[Category:Military history of India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2020}}\n'''Purbiya''' (or '''Purabia''') was a common term used in medieval India for [[Rajput]]-led mercenaries and soldiers from the eastern [[Gangetic Plain]] - areas corresponding to present-day western [[Bihar]] and eastern [[Uttar Pradesh]].<ref name=\"Naravane1999\"/> ''Purbiya Rajputs'' translates as Eastern Rajputs.<ref name=\"ErnstPati2007\">{{cite book|author1=Waltraud Ernst|author2=Biswamoy Pati|title=India's Princely States: People, Princes and Colonialism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9eKbW3ukh9oC&pg=PA57|date=18 October 2007|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=978-1-134-11988-2|page=57}}</ref> In contrast, the Rajputs living in [[Rajasthan]] were historically referred to as \"Western Rajputs\".<ref name=\"Naravane1999\">{{cite book|author=M. S. Naravane|title=The Rajputs of Rajputana: A Glimpse of Medieval Rajasthan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lF0FvjG3GWEC&pg=PA23|year=1999|publisher=APH Publishing|isbn=978-81-7648-118-2|page=23}}</ref>\n\n==Recruitment==\nThe core region for Purbiya recruitment was the [[Bhojpuri region|Bhojpur]] region of modern-day Western [[Bihar]] and Eastern [[Uttar Pradesh]].<ref name=Kolff2013>{{cite journal | jstor=j.ctt6wp6pg.11 | title=Peasants fighting for a living in early modern North India | journal=Fighting for a Living | author= Dirk H.A. Kolff | publisher= Amsterdam University Press | year=2013 | pages= 243\u2013266}}</ref> The [[Ujjainiya]] clan of Rajputs were the main territorial lords of this region and they played the role of specialised recruiting agents and commanders of these Purbiya soldiers who were usually young peasant men native to Bhojpur.<ref name=Kolff2013 /> The soldiers gained a great reputation among the lords and kings of Northern and Western India and the Ujjainiyas used this to raise their status among other Rajput clans.<ref name=Kolff2013 />\n\nMany future Purbiya mercenaries would carry out a pilgrimage to [[Buxar]] in modern-day Bihar where they would immerse themselves in a ''tiger tank''. During this process, the young peasant would see themselves as being reborn as a \"fearless warrior\".<ref name=Kolff2013 />\n\n==History==\n[[File:Camel Rider,.jpg|thumb|A Purbiya camel rider in [[Bihar]], [[India]] in 1825.]]\n\nThe [[Mughal Empire|Mughals]] were among the first groups to enter into the military labour market and start recruiting Purbiyas. Mughal sources detail a diwan of Bihar [[subah]] attempting to collect soldiers in [[Buxar]] to serve the emperor.<ref name=\"Kolff2002\">{{cite book|author=Dirk H. A. Kolff|title=Naukar, Rajput, and Sepoy: The Ethnohistory of the Military Labour Market of Hindustan, 1450-1850|url=https://books.google.com/?id=SrdiVPsFRYIC&pg=PA169&dq=Kolff+Mughal+province#v=onepage&q=Kolff%20Mughal%20province&f=false|date=8 August 2002|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=978-0-521-52305-9|page=59}}</ref>\n\nThe rulers of [[Malwa]] were also keen recruiters due to Purbiyas' expertise with firearms. This expertise may have been gained due to the easy availability of [[saltpetre]] in their native areas.<ref>{{cite book|first1=Waltraud |last1=Ernst |first2=Biswamoy |last2=Pati |title=India's Princely States: People, Princes and Colonialism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9eKbW3ukh9oC&pg=PA57|year=2007|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-11988-2|page=57}}</ref> Most Purbiyas were mercenaries and were paid for their services but some were actual kings of smaller principalities.<ref name=\"Naravane1999\"/><ref>Journal of Indian history, Volume 66, Dept. of History, University of Kerala, 1988</ref>{{Pn|date=October 2016}} This recruitment drive from Malwa saw the large influx of Purbiya soldiers into the region. Many of the local chieftains in Malwa depended heavily on Purbiya soldiers such as [[Silhadi]] who eventually became known as a Purbiya himself.<ref name=\"Kolff2002\" />\nThe presence of Purbiya mercenaries in [[Gujarat]] are referenced in 16th and 17th century [[Persian language|Persian]] chronicles including many Purbiya gunners serving in the army of Bahadur Shah of the [[Gujarat Sultanate]] in 1535.<ref name=Khan1999>{{cite journal | title=Re-examining the origin and group identity of the so-called \"Purbias\", 1500-1800 | author= Iqtidar Alam Khan | journal=Proceedings of the Indian History Congress |volume = 60| year=1999 | pages= 363\u2013371|jstor = 44144102}}</ref>\n\nPurbiyas had a long tradition of being recruited as mercenaries for various rulers such as the [[British Raj|British]]<ref name=\"Hiltebeitel2009\">{{cite book|author=Alf Hiltebeitel|title=Rethinking India's Oral and Classical Epics: Draupadi among Rajputs, Muslims, and Dalits|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MMFdosx0PokC&pg=PA308|date=15 February 2009|publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]]|isbn=978-0-226-34055-5|page=308|author-link=Alf Hiltebeitel}}</ref><ref name=\"Karsten2013\">{{cite book|first=Peter|last=Karsten|title=Recruiting, Drafting, and Enlisting: Two Sides of the Raising of Military Forces|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Fh_fAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA103|date=31 October 2013|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=978-1-135-66150-2|page=103}}</ref> and the [[Marathas]].<ref name=\"ErnstPati2007\" /> Purbiyas made up the majority of the [[Bengal Army]].<ref name=\"Karsten2013\" />Prior to 1857, the British [[East India Company]] preferred to recruit Purbiya soldiers, who they designated as \"The fighting tribes of the Hindoos and the Musselmen\", or simply \"Easterners\".<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=627fBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA335 |title=Chinese and Indian Warfare \u2013 From the Classical Age to 1870 |first1=Kaushik |last1=Roy |first2=Peter |last2=Lorge |page=335|isbn=9781317587101 |date=2014-12-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Philip|last=Mason|pages=229 & 573|title=A Matter of Honour|isbn=978-0-333-41837-6|year=1986}}</ref> The [[Bengal Army]] of the East India Company preferred to recruit its sepoys from the [[Brahmin]]s and Rajputs of Awadh and Bihar, in part because they had an average height of 5'8\", an important consideration in an army that valued impressive appearance amongst its soldiers.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=vRE3n1VwDTIC&pg=PA214 |title=Hinduism and the Ethics of Warfare in South Asia: From Antiquity to the Present |first=Kaushik |last=Roy |year=2012 |page=214|isbn=9781107017368 }}</ref>\n\n===1857 mutiny===\n[[File:Bengal Troops on the Line of March (6125141926).jpg|thumb|400px|Bengal troops in the 19th century (1840s), the majority of troops in the Bengal Army were Purbiyas]]\nThe Purbiya units of the Bengal Army played a major role in the [[Indian Rebellion of 1857]] against the British. [[Mangal Pandey]], a notable figure during the start of the mutiny, was a Purbiya serving in the 34th [[Bengal Native Infantry]]. Following the suppression of the uprising, British authorities decided not to recruit troops from the eastern plains, and the new Bengal Army was to be recruited primarily from the [[Sikh]] and [[Islam in India|Muslim]] communities of the [[Punjab]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=q5JECgAAQBAJ&pg=PA6 |title=Military Manpower, Armies and Warfare in South Asia |first=Kaushik |last=Roy |page=6|isbn=9781317321286 |date=2015-10-06 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Philip|last=Mason|page=305|title=A Matter of Honour|isbn=978-0-333-41837-6|year=1986}}</ref> Purbiya recruitment from the western regions of the [[United Provinces of Agra and Oudh|United Provinces]] and the [[Delhi]] region continued but on a much smaller scale (two out of sixty-four regiments by 1893).<ref>{{cite book|first=Saul|last=David|page=404|title=The Indian Mutiny|isbn=978-0-141-00554-6|date=2003-09-04}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mercenaries in India]]\n*[[Camel cavalry]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* M K A Siddiqui (ed.), ''Marginal Muslim Communities in India'', Institute of Objective Studies, New Delhi (2004)\n* [[Dasharatha Sharma]] ''Rajasthan through the Ages'' a comprehensive and authentic history of Rajasthan, prepared under the orders of the Government of Rajasthan. First published 1966 by Rajasthan Archives.\n\n[[Category:Rajputs|*]]\n[[Category:History of Bihar]]\n[[Category:Mercenary units and formations of the Early Modern era]]\n[[Category:Military history of India]]\n", "name_user": "Ajpfrgvcc", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Purbiyas_(soldiers)"}
{"title_page": "Sukant Kadam", "text_new": "<br />\n{{Infobox badminton player\n|name=Sukant Kadam\n|image= Sukant Kadam.jpg\n|image_size= \n|caption=\n|birth_date= {{Birth date and age|1993|05|09|df=yes}}\n|height= 170&nbsp;cm\n|weight= 60&nbsp;kg\n|country= {{IND}}\n|event= MS SL4\n|medaltemplates={{MedalCountry|{{IND}}}}\n{{MedalSport|Men SL4 Para-Badminton player}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[BWF Para-Badminton World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2019|[[2019 BWF Para-Badminton World Championships|Basel, Switzerland]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|Asian Para Games}}\n{{MedalBronze|2018|Men's Team}}\n{{MedalCompetition|Asian Championships}}\n{{MedalBronze|2016|Asian Para-Badminton Championship}}}}\n'''Sukant Indukant Kadam''' (born 9 May 1993) is an Indian professional [[Para-Badminton]] player. Having made his international debut in 2014, he became world number 2 in the SL4 category on 12 June 2017.<ref name=\"HT-20170717\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/pune-news/pune-s-para-badminton-player-sukant-kadam-becomes-world-no-2/story-tuNcXBWpGXhiQJGZNhN9uJ.html |title=Sukant Kadam becomes World No 2 |date=17 July 2017 |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |location=Pune |author=Staff }}</ref> He won his first title at the Uganda Para-Badminton International 2017.<ref name=\"BWF-20191010\">{{Cite web |url=https://bwfpara.tournamentsoftware.com/sport/player.aspx?id=58EB12CC-845E-40B5-85AD-AD5C6F2E2295&player=53 |title=BWF Para-Badminton{{Snd}} Uganda Para-Badminton International 2017{{Snd}} Players{{Snd}} Sukant Kadam |date=10 October 2019 |website=bwfpara.tournamentsoftware.com |access-date=2 April 2020 }}</ref> He currently lives in [[Pune]], Maharashtra. He was appointed as a Taluka Sports Officer by the Government of Maharashtra.<ref name=\"MGIN-20190104\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.maharashtra.gov.in/site/Upload/Government%20Resolutions/Marathi/201901041126415321.pdf |format=PDF |title=\u0936\u093e\u0938\u0928 \u0927\u0928\u0923\u0923\u092f \u0915\u094d\u0930\u092e\u093e\u0902\u0915\u0903 \u0916\u0947\u0906\u0915\u094d\u0937 1517/\u092a\u094d\u0930.\u0915\u094d\u0930.151/\u0915\u094d\u0930\u0940\u092f\u0941\u0938\u0947-2 |trans-title=Govt. Establishment Number: Kheaxa 1517 / Q.151 / Creuse-2<!-- Please confirm/provide a better translation--> |date=4 January 2019 |website=[[Government of Maharashtra]] |language=Marathi }}</ref>\n\nDuring Sukant's first year of Mechanical engineering in January 2011 in [[Government College Of Engineering And Research, Avasari Khurd]] he was rejected from the class team because of his slow movement. After a year of practice and hard work, he got a chance to play on his college team.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://thebridge.in/featured/sukant-kadams-incredible-story-from-a-college-team-reject-to-becoming-world-no-2/ |title=Sukant Kadam's incredible story{{Snd}} from a college team reject to becoming World No.2 |date=15 June 2018 |work=The Bridge |first1=Sounak |last1=Mullick |location=Bengaluru }}</ref> In 2012 Para Athlete [[Girisha Nagarajegowda]] won Silver medal in High Jump (F42) [[2012 Summer Paralympics]].<ref>https://www.news18.com/news/india/paralympics-girisha-wins-indias-1st-medal-504463.html</ref> This is how [[Sukant Kadam]] got to know about [[Paralympic sports]] and [[Para-badminton]]. He made his debut at the England Para Badminton International 2014.<ref>https://be.tournamentsoftware.com/sport/player.aspx?id=A54B7002-1ED7-434A-A5E0-F8AC742F08BA&player=94</ref>\n\n== Medals ==\n* 2019{{Snd}} bronze medal at the [[2019 BWF Para-Badminton World Championships|BWF Para Badminton World Championships]]\n* 2018{{Snd}} bronze medal at the [[Badminton at the 2018 Asian Para Games|Asian Para Games]]\n* 2016{{Snd}} bronze medal in MD SL3-SL4 at the Para-Badminton Asian Championships <ref>https://bwfpara.tournamentsoftware.com/sport/winners.aspx?id=C88ED65D-5F60-4652-B853-C72E8CE34C0F</ref> <ref>http://www.gobadminton.in/para-badminton/816/sukant-kadam-beyond-boundaries</ref> \n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kadam, Sukant}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Paralympic athletes of India]]\n[[Category:Indian male Para-badminton players]]\n[[Category:Indian male Badminton players]]\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Autobiography|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox badminton player\n|name=Sukant Kadam\n|image= Sukant Kadam.jpg\n|image_size= \n|caption=\n|birth_date= {{Birth date and age|1993|05|09|df=yes}}\n|height= 170&nbsp;cm\n|weight= 60&nbsp;kg\n|country= {{IND}}\n|event=\n|medaltemplates={{MedalCountry|{{IND}}}}\n{{MedalSport|Men SL4 Para-Badminton player}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[BWF Para-Badminton World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|2019|[[2019 BWF Para-Badminton World Championships|Basel, Switzerland]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|Asian Para Games}}\n{{MedalBronze|2018|Men's Team}}\n{{MedalCompetition|Asian Championships}}\n{{MedalBronze|2016|Asian Para-Badminton Championship}}}}\n'''Sukant Indukant Kadam''' (born 9 May 1993) is an Indian professional Para Badminton player. Having made his international debut in 2014, he became world number 2 in the SL4 category on 12 June 2017.<ref name=\"HT-20170717\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/pune-news/pune-s-para-badminton-player-sukant-kadam-becomes-world-no-2/story-tuNcXBWpGXhiQJGZNhN9uJ.html |title=Sukant Kadam becomes World No 2 |date=17 July 2017 |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |location=Pune |author=Staff }}</ref> He won his first title at the Uganda Para-Badminton International 2017.<ref name=\"BWF-20191010\">{{Cite web |url=https://bwfpara.tournamentsoftware.com/sport/player.aspx?id=58EB12CC-845E-40B5-85AD-AD5C6F2E2295&player=53 |title=BWF Para-Badminton{{Snd}} Uganda Para-Badminton International 2017{{Snd}} Players{{Snd}} Sukant Kadam |date=10 October 2019 |website=bwfpara.tournamentsoftware.com |access-date=2 April 2020 }}</ref> He currently lives in [[Pune]], Maharashtra. He was appointed as a Taluka Sports Officer by the Government of Maharashtra.<ref name=\"MGIN-20190104\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.maharashtra.gov.in/site/Upload/Government%20Resolutions/Marathi/201901041126415321.pdf |format=PDF |title=\u0936\u093e\u0938\u0928 \u0927\u0928\u0923\u0923\u092f \u0915\u094d\u0930\u092e\u093e\u0902\u0915\u0903 \u0916\u0947\u0906\u0915\u094d\u0937 1517/\u092a\u094d\u0930.\u0915\u094d\u0930.151/\u0915\u094d\u0930\u0940\u092f\u0941\u0938\u0947-2 |trans-title=Govt. Establishment Number: Kheaxa 1517 / Q.151 / Creuse-2<!-- Please confirm/provide a better translation--> |date=4 January 2019 |website=[[Government of Maharashtra]] |language=Marathi }}</ref>\n\nDuring Kadam's first year of engineering,{{Clarify|date=April 2020|reason=Engineering what? School? Where?}} he was rejected from the class team because of his slow movement. After a year of practice and hard work, he got a chance to play on his college team.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://thebridge.in/featured/sukant-kadams-incredible-story-from-a-college-team-reject-to-becoming-world-no-2/ |title=Sukant Kadam's incredible story{{Snd}} from a college team reject to becoming World No.2 |date=15 June 2018 |work=The Bridge |first1=Sounak |last1=Mullick |location=Bengaluru }}</ref> In 2012 Para Athlete Girish N, Gowda won Bronze medal in London Paralympics.{{Clarify|date=April 2020|reason=Who is this and why is it relevant?}} This is how Kadam got to know about Para Sports and Para Badminton. He made his debut at the England Para Badminton International 2014.\n\n== Medals ==\n* 2019{{Snd}} bronze medal at the [[2019 BWF Para-Badminton World Championships|BWF Para Badminton World Championships]]\n* 2018{{Snd}} bronze medal at the [[Badminton at the 2018 Asian Para Games|Asian Para Games]]\n* 2016{{Snd}} bronze medal in men's doubles at the Para-Badminton Asian Championships<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n<!--<ref>https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/spotlight/para-badminton-player-sukant-kadam-speaks-abou